Summaries

five sample summaries

[1] Josephine Philips presents a simple yet powerful solution to address the global waste and environmental issues caused by fast fashion. She begins with the personal story of her grandmother's 60-year-old dress, highlighting how the modern culture of "hyper-disposability" has caused us to lose sight of the value of our clothing. This culture results in the annual disposal of 92 million metric tons of garments, creating monumental problems such as the pile of discarded clothes in the Atacama Desert, now visible from space, and the huge influx of used clothes into developing nations. This staggering amount of waste, combined with the fashion industry's carbon emissions which exceed all international air travel creates an unsustainable system. Philips's proposal is a shift in mindset: to correctly value our clothes. She emphasizes that instead of discarding an item because it's slightly ripped, we should, like her sister with her cherished jeans, care for it, repair it, and alter it to fit our bodies. Her company, SoJO, aims to rebuild this culture of repair and tailoring. She concludes powerfully that loving and cherishing our clothes brings personal joy and deeper connection, and ultimately, valuing the things that we own is a climate solution.
[2] This talk explains a very big issue in the fashion world today. Many people buy cheap clothes very fast, and they also throw them away very fast. Because of this, the world has a huge amount of waste. Every second, a truck full of clothes is burned or put in the ground. The speaker says that many of these clothes are still good. They only have small problems, like a broken button, a short rip, or a zipper that does not move well. These small problems can be fixed very easily and fast. However, many people do not fix their clothes because they think it is hard, or they do not know where they can go to repair them. She believes that if more people fix their clothes, they will buy less, waste less, and help the earth. She also says that fixing clothes lets people keep their favorite items longer, and this can make fashion more personal and more meaningful. Her message is that we should pause before buying something and ask by ourselves if we really need it. She asked us to think about the work behind the items, the meaning it might have in our lives, and whether we will value it later.                                                                                                                                                                  
[3] Her grandmother wore the dress. Her grandmother teaches the same lesson about what it truly means of value. She found a tech company. Now is a  fast fashion generation. People think about new clothes on Instagram. It is absolutely devastating. 50millions items slow down each week. Her sister loves the jeans. She continued to wear it for 15 years. It is truly valuable. She has a true and deeper happiness with the jeans. She should not slow it. We need to think about our effect on the environment of the earth. I have to imagine the negative effects and effects on others. And, do we have to think that we need these clothes? when we buy some clothes. We have to imagine the future with these clothes.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           
[4] The speaker begins by sharing the story of her grandmothers dress, a garment kept and cherished for sixty years. Through this dress, she learned the importance of valuing what we own. She contrasts this with the fast-fashion culture she grew up in, where people buy quickly, discard quickly, and rarely think about the impact. She explains how unwanted clothes often end up in places like Ghana or the Atacama Desert, forming massive piles of waste that can even be seen from space. The fashion industrys carbon emissions, she notes, are higher than those of international air travel. To change this, she argues that we must shift our mindset from disposability to longevity by repairing, tailoring, and appreciating our clothes. She uses her sisters 15-year-old jeansrepaired twice and filled with memoriesas an example of how garments can grow in value and meaning over time. She concludes that caring for what we own is not only emotionally fulfilling but also a real climate solution.]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           
[5] Today, especially in the young generation, people buy many clothes without thinking much. All we think about is whats right in front of us, such as trends. Therefore, we can see mountains of clothes from space in Ghana or Chile. In this kind of situation, the speaker Philips says we should rethink how we deal with clothes. She used to be one of the people who buys many and throws away many. However, getting a dress from her grandmother, which her grandmother wore and cherished for many years, changed her mind. She started to think, clothes can have value. However, to make value in it, the clothes need humans power such as caring or repairing or taking time. Also, she says we are the ones who are buying and throwing away many. Therefore, we are the ones obstructing the achievement of the SDGs. She says the solution to this situation is to buy less stuff and look after what we buy.

five sample opinions

[1] I am not very interested in clothes, so I go to a clothing shop two or three times a year and buy one or two clothes. Wear the same clothes until they are perforated or worn out, and when they are no longer worn, use them as a cloth and reuse them. There are no people around me who buy clothes in bulk and dispose of them in bulk, but I thought there might be a lot of people like influencers and celebrities who do public work like that. Even if you wear less clothes, you can change the combination to a different fashion. I thought that small ingenuity could reduce excessive purchase and mass consumption of clothes.
[2]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              
[3] I learned that a large amount of waste clothes are sent to South America and Africa and then they are burned. It is also a problem,but it leads to spreading earth warming because of burning them.The cheap waste clothes,which arent sold in the market are sold in Africa and it leads to disturb African clothes commerce. People selling clothes in Africa are suffering from the price of clothes. I agree with the idea that we should think deeply about whether this item is really needed for me or not.                                                                                                                          
[4] Wastes of clothes are a serious issue, especially, developed countries. Fast fashion is a present trend in the world. The trend focuses on supplying fad clothes for consumers more speedily. Consumers can get trendy items more cheaply and freely, but people get tired of these clothes more rapidly. As a result, a lot of clothes are thrown away and sent to developing countries, for example, South America or Africa. Fast fashion is popular among people in developed countries mainly. However, people in developing countries bear the burden of the clothes. People should reflect on the situation.                          
[5]
